1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE BILL 3915 By: Dollens
4
5
6
7 AS INTRODUCED
8 An Act relating to animal population; creating the
Oklahoma Spay and Neuter Grant Program; providing the
9 Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food and Forestry
will oversee the program; providing purpose of
10 program; providing Department shall award grants
based upon recommendation of the Spay and Neuter
11 Grant Program Advisory Board; providing Board
membership; prohibiting compensation for Board
12 members; providing for travel expenses; providing
role of Board; providing who may seek a grant;
13 providing competitive grant proposal requirements;
providing for review of competitive grant proposals;
14 providing for promulgation of rules; amending 47 O.S.
2021, Section 1104.10, as amended by Section 17,
15 Chapter 171, O.S.L. 2025 (47 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
1104.10), which relates to the Animal Friendly
16 Revolving Fund; modifying purpose of fund; amending
47 O.S. 2021, Section 1135.5, as last amended by
17 Section 1, Chapter 358, O.S.L. 2025 (47 O.S. Supp.
2025, Section 1135.5), which relates to special
18 license plates; removing provision that allows
purchaser to choose where fee is to be deposited;
19 providing that a certain portion of the fee collected
for the animal friendly special license plate is to
20 be deposited in the Animal Friendly Revolving Fund;
providing for recodification; providing for
21 codification; and providing an effective date.
22
23
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
Req. No. 14378 Page 1

1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 901 of Title 4, unless there is
3 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. There is hereby created the Oklahoma Spay and Neuter Grant
5 Program which shall be overseen and carried out by the Oklahoma
6 Department of Agriculture, Food and Forestry.
7 B. The purpose of this program is to reduce animal shelter
8 overpopulation and cat and dog euthanasia rates by financing grants
9 to local governments and animal welfare organizations for programs
10 that most efficiently and effectively facilitate and promote the
11 provision of spay and neuter services for cats and dogs in the
12 state.
13 C. Grants shall be awarded by the Department based upon the
14 recommendation of the of the Oklahoma Spay and Neuter Grant Program
15 Advisory Board.
16 D. The Oklahoma Spay and Neuter Grant Program Advisory Board
17 shall consist of:
18 1. The Commissioner of Agriculture, Food and Forestry, or his
19 or her designee; and
20 2. The following members, who shall be appointed by the
21 Commissioner of Agriculture, Food and Forestry:
22 a. one representative of a private animal shelter located
23 in Oklahoma,
24 b. one Oklahoma veterinarian,
Req. No. 14378 Page 2

1 c. one representative of an Oklahoma animal control
2 agency, and
3 d. two representatives of animal welfare advocacy
4 organizations.
5 E. The Commissioner of Agriculture, Food and Forestry shall
6 designate the chair of the Board.
7 F. Members of the Board:
8 1. May not receive compensation as a member of the Board; and
9 2. Are entitled to reimbursement for expenses related to
10 travel.
11 G. The Board shall advise the Department with respect to:
12 1. The administration of the Oklahoma Spay and Neuter Grant
13 Program;
14 2. The solicitation and evaluation of competitive grant
15 proposals;
16 3. The creation of additional standards for grant proposals;
17 4. Additional relevant data that the Department should require
18 from local animal shelters and appropriate animal control
19 organizations; and
20 5. Any other appropriate matter with respect to the
21 implementation of this program in the discretion of the Department.
22 H. Grants may be sought by local governments or animal welfare
23 organizations to facilitate and promote the provisions of spay and
24 neuter services for cats and dogs by submitting a competitive grant
Req. No. 14378 Page 3

1 prop osal to the Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food and
2 Forestry.
3 I. A competitive grant proposal:
4 1. Shall target low-income communities and populations to the
5 maximum extent possible and detail how that goal is to be
6 accomplished;
7 2. May target feral cat populations if the Department
8 determines that this targeting does not violate local law;
9 3. Shall efficiently and effectively facilitate and promote the
10 provisions of spay and neuter services for cats and dogs; and
11 4. May include public education and outreach components.
12 J. The Department shall evaluate a competitive grant proposal
13 based on:
14 1. The standards established under subsection I of this
15 section; and
16 2. Any additional standards the Department promulgates by rule
17 consistent with this section.
18 K. The Department shall promulgate rules to promulgate this act
19 which shall include requiring a grant recipient to report relevant
20 information on how the grant was used, including data on the number
21 and type of spay or neuter surgeries performed and a description of
22 any public education and outreach implemented.
